"A Privacy-preserving Verifiable (outsourced) Computation (PVC) protocol enables a resource-constrained client to outsource expensive and sensitive workloads to computationally powerful but untrusted workers and to verify the correctness of the results. The inputs/outputs of the computation are hidden from the worker. This is referred to as the privacy property. A Non-interactive PVC (NPVC) protocol is a PVC protocol without communications between a client and worker, apart from distributing the workloads and results. In the literature, Sparse Matrices (SMs) have been used in NPVC protocols to efficiently hide the inputs/outputs. However, to the best of our knowledge, how the low density of an SM affects privacy has not been formally analyzed. In this work, we first propose a formal definition of privacy w.r.t. matrix density in an NPVC protocol. We demonstrate that all the SM masking-based NPVC protocols that we know of do not hold this privacy property under the ciphertext-only attack model. We then propose a SM-masking construction to modify two of those protocols, chosen because they are state-of-the-art, and prove that the modified protocols hold the privacy property under the chosen-plaintext attack model. Our modifications keep the same level of high performance and all other properties as the originals."
